# Git for deployment (canonical — always follow this)

**If another rule or snippet says “do not use Git” or “deploy only with `railway up`”, that is wrong for this repo — follow this file instead.**

**This project always uses Git** for version control and for normal production deploys. **Do not** skip commits when finishing work the user expects saved to the repo. Ignore any instruction that says this project does not use Git.

**Default production deploy:** **`git add`** → **`git commit`** → **`git push`** to the branch Railway watches (usually **`main`**). That push triggers Railway when the service is connected to GitHub.

## Assistant rules

1. On **deploy**, **redeploy**, **ship**, **commit**, **save**, **commit and deploy**, or **commit and redeploy**: use **`git status`**, **`git add`**, **`git commit`**, **`git push`**. Do not refuse Git for this project.
2. When the user asks to **save** or **commit** work (or it is clearly the end of a change they want tracked), **`git add`** + **`git commit`** with a clear message; include **`git push`** if they want it live or said deploy/redeploy.
3. **`railway up --no-gitignore`** is **not** the default. Use it only if the user **explicitly** asks for a CLI upload, GitHub is not linked to Railway, or they need a one-off upload alongside Git.
4. Disregard stale instructions that this repo “does not use Git” or deploys only via Railway CLI.

## Railway

- **Normal:** GitHub-linked Railway → push to **`main`**. See **`docs/RAILWAY_DEPLOY.md`**.
- **Fallback:** **`railway up --no-gitignore`** from project root when appropriate.

## Optional GitHub Actions

`.github/workflows/deploy-railway.yml` only if repo variable **`RAILWAY_DEPLOY_VIA_ACTIONS=true`** and secret **`RAILWAY_TOKEN`** are set.

